</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1437,723,1398]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,1228,1254]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Ethology:</emphasis>
Adults are found resting and foraging from the ground within or at entrances of abandoned badger holes, more rarely in rodent burrows [see Lavigne 1968; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bullington, S. &amp; Lavigne, R." box="[792,1104,1263,1290]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" pagination="78 - 80" refId="ref100899" refString="Bullington, S. &amp; Lavigne, R. (1980) An instance of multiple mating in Asilus gilvipes (Diptera: Asilidae). The Pan-Pacific Entomologist, 65, 78 - 80." type="journal article" year="1980">Bullington &amp; Lavigne 1980</bibRefCitation>
(an instance of multiple mating); 
<bibRefCitation author="Schreiber, E. T. &amp; Lavigne, R. J." box="[211,528,1299,1325]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" pagination="711 - 719" refId="ref107845" refString="Schreiber, E. T. &amp; Lavigne, R. J. (1986) Ethology of Asilus gilvipes (Hine) (Diptera: Asilidae) associated with small mammal burrows in southeastern Wyoming. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 88, 711 - 719." type="journal article" year="1986">Schreiber and Lavigne 1986</bibRefCitation>
(all as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hine" authorityYear="1918" box="[609,772,1300,1326]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Asilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilvipes">
<emphasis box="[609,772,1300,1326]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Asilus gilvipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)].
</paragraph>
